{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16420"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16420"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.07,0.22,0.07,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9111"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65779"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9111"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16420"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51219"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1758"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2474"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43633"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44435"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65779","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65779"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of productive cough and fatigue. She has lost 4 kg in weight over this period. She has a medical history of bronchiectasis diagnosed five years ago. Her only regular medication is azithromycin. She is a lifelong non-smoker. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals scattered crackles bilaterally. A chest CT shows bronchiectasis with new tree-in-bud nodular infiltrates, raising suspicion for non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection. Three sputum samples have been collected but are negative on acid-fast staining.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Empiric clarithromycin therapy","Mantoux test","Interferon gamma release assay","Empiric high-dose amoxicillin","Bronchoscopy with washings"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of non-tuberculous mycobacterial (NTM) infection, including chronic productive cough, weight loss, and characteristic CT findings of bronchiectasis with nodular infiltrates. NTM are environmental organisms found in soil and water, distinct from \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E. The most common cause of NTM lung disease is \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium avium\u003C/em\u003E complex (MAC).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with washings\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it provides the best specimens for culture. This is particularly important in patients with bronchiectasis where sputum samples may be contaminated with oral flora. Bronchial washings provide a more reliable specimen for identifying NTM species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon gamma release assay\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EMantoux test\u003C/strong\u003E are used to detect \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E infection but do not help diagnose NTM infection. These tests may cross-react with some NTM species but are not reliable for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpiric clarithromycin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate without first confirming the diagnosis and identifying the specific NTM species. Treatment typically involves a combination of a macrolide (clarithromycin or azithromycin), ethambutol, and rifampicin for MAC infection, but susceptibility testing is essential as resistance patterns vary between species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-dose amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E would not be effective against NTM and would be an inappropriate choice given the clinical suspicion for mycobacterial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike tuberculosis, which is transmitted person-to-person, NTM infections are acquired from environmental exposure. The diagnosis requires both appropriate clinical features and multiple positive cultures from respiratory specimens. NTM infections are increasingly recognised in immunocompetent individuals, with rising rates reported worldwide. This represents a significant shift from historical understanding where these infections were primarily associated with immunocompromised hosts. Treatment is challenging and typically involves a combination of antibiotics for at least 12 months, with the specific regimen depending on the NTM species identified and its susceptibility pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection requires multiple positive cultures from respiratory specimens for diagnosis.","Bronchiectasis and nodular infiltrates on chest CT are characteristic radiological findings in non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection."],"references":["Ratnatunga CN, Lutzky VP, Kupz A, Doolan DL, Reid DW, Field M, et al. The rise of non-tuberculosis mycobacterial lung disease. Frontiers in immunology. 2020 Mar 3;11:303. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32194556/","Sharma SK, Upadhyay V. Epidemiology, diagnosis \u0026 treatment of non-tuberculous mycobacterial diseases. Indian Journal of Medical Research. 2020 Sep 1;152(3):185-226. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33107481/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51219"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16420"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51219"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T20:43:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T15:53:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9111"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65779"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","